==English==

===Etymology===
From Latin ''[[pontificare]]'', '''pontificate''', from ''[[pontifex]]'', '''bridge builder''', ancient Roman title taken by the bishops of Rome

===Pronunciation 1===
*{{IPA|/pɒnˈtɪfɪkeɪt/}} (''[[RP]]'')
*{{IPA|/pɑːnˈtɪfɪkeɪt/}} (''US'')
*{{audio|en-us-pontificate.ogg|Audio (US)}}

====Intransitive verb====
{{en-verb|ponificat|ed}}

# To [[speak]] at length or be unnecessarily [[wordy]], often in a [[patronizing]] or [[pompous]] manner.
# To [[express]] one's position as if it is [[absolutely]] [[correct]].
# To [[preside]], as at a [[religious]] ceremony.

===Pronunciation 2===
*{{IPA|/pɒnˈtɪfɪkət/}} (''[[RP]]'')
*{{IPA|/pɑːnˈtɪfɪkət/}} (''US'')
*{{audio|en-us-pontificate_noun.ogg|Audio (US)}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The [[term of office]] of a [[pope]].

